<DOC><DOCNO> AP880415-0164 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 1635EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-ASNE-Officers     04-15 0239</FIRST><SECOND>AM-ASNE-Officers,230</SECOND><HEAD>USA Today Official Named President of Editors Group</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   John Seigenthaler, editorial director of USAToday, was elected president of the 1,000-member American Societyof Newspaper Editors on Friday, stepping in for a Wall StreetJournal editor who was unable to take the job because of healthreasons.   Seigenthaler, who also is editor and publisher of the NashvilleTennessean, had been ASNE treasurer.   Edward R. Cony, associate editor of the Wall Street Journal, whofor the past year served as vice president of the ASNE, was electedto the presidency, but an ASNE statement said he was resigning thepost.   By tradition, the vice president usually succeeds to thepresidency. But, the statement said, Cony discovered in early Marchthat he was suffering from Alzheimer's disease, a progressive braincell degeneration that leads to senility. There is no cure for thedisease.   Katherine Fanning, editor of the Christian Science Monitor andoutgoing ASNE president, announced Cony's election and his decisionto resign at a luncheon on the final day of the ASNE's annualconvention. Cony received a standing ovation.   Cony, who has been a member of ASNE since 1971, previouslyserved as the group's secretary and treasurer.   Other new officers are Loren Ghiglione, editor and publisher ofthe Southbridge (Mass.) News, vice president; Burl Osborne, editorand publisher of The Dallas Morning News, secretary; and DavidLawrence, publisher of The Detroit Free Press, treasurer.</TEXT></DOC>